7¤Checking movements on your account
:SKRSLUT.
.sp 3mm
:SWISS8.
You are obliged to check the movements on your account on an ongoing
basis. If you discover any transactions which do not match your
receipts or which you believe have not been made by you, you must
contact &BANKNAVN. without undue delay. In this context, be aware of
the deadlines stated in Sections 8 and 9.
.sp 3mm
In connection with your ongoing checks of the movements on your
account, note that when you use your card to make purchases on the
Internet or via mail/telephone order, the business you deal
with should not debit the sum from your account until the
goods in question have been shipped. However, when you book airline
tickets or concert tickets, the company will normally debit the
amount as soon as you book the travel or order the tickets.
.sp 5mm
.kp off
.kp on
:SWISS10.
:FED.
8¤Reversing payments you
.us have
approved
:SKRSLUT.
.sp 3mm
:SWISS8.
:FED.
8.1¤If you did not know the final sum when approving the transaction
:SKRSLUT.
.br
If you did not know the final sum when you approved the payment, and if
the sum subsequently debited from your account is significantly higher
than what you could reasonably have expected, you may be entitled to
reverse the payment.
This may, for example, occur in connection with
renting a car or checking out from a hotel, when you have allowed the
business or hotel to debit your account for refuelling the vehicle or
restocking the mini-bar.
.sp 3mm
.kp off
.kp on
You must contact &BANKNAVN. within eight weeks of the sum having been
withdrawn from your account if you believe that you are entitled to
reverse a payment for which you have not approved the final sum.
complaint with &BANKNAVN. within 14 days of becoming aware of a
possible claim. When assessing whether you have submitted your
complaint to &BANKNAVN. in time, emphasis will be placed on your duty
to review your account movements on a regular basis, see Section 7.
.sp 3mm
.kp off
.kp on
&BANKNAVN. will then investigate your complaint. While your complaint
is being investigated, the sum in dispute will normally be credited to
your account. If your complaint subsequently proves to be unjustified, the
bank will withdraw the sum from your account once more.
